This page collects helpful resources — Web sites, books, journals, and so on — to assist in writing good mathematics articles. To follow the [[Wikipedia:scientific citation guidelines|scientific citation guidelines]] adopted by [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Mathematics|WikiProject Mathematics]], every article should cite high quality sources where readers can learn more about the topic. In the spirit of Wikipedia, most sources listed here can be freely viewed and downloaded without charge and without access restrictions, thus they are particularly convenient for both editors and readers alike. As well, some tools are listed to help find and format citation data.

Editors can request access to specific articles or books or information on a specific topic at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Resource Exchange/Resource Request]].

==Source formats and viewing options==
Many valuable references in mathematics are beginning to migrate from inaccessible libraries to scans available on the web. This includes both classical publications and recent ones. The most common document formats are:
# '''[[HTML]]''': Hypertext markup language, the standard web browsing format
# '''[[PDF]]''': Portable document format, the [[Adobe Acrobat]] format
# '''[[PostScript|PS]]''': PostScript, [[Adobe]]'s format for printing
# '''[[DjVu]]''': a compact format for scanned documents
# '''[[DVI (file format)|DVI]]''': Device independent format, produced by [[TeX]]
Scans of historical works are significantly more compact in DjVu as compared to PDF, and often the text can be searched. Readers for this popular format can be [http://www.djvuzone.org/download/index.html downloaded] and used at no cost. Adobe's PS (and PDF) format can be imaged for viewing using a [[Ghostscript]] implementation (with Ghostview), which also can be [http://www.cs.wisc.edu/~ghost/ downloaded] and used freely. On [[Linux]] systems, the [[Evince]] viewer can handle DVI as well as other formats, and DVI viewers are also available freely available from [http://www.lizardtech.com/download/dl_options.php?page=doc LizardTech] for [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[Mac OS]] systems.

==Websites with extensive coverage of mathematical topics==

*[http://planetmath.org PlanetMath] — [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Mathematics|WikiProject Mathematics]] exchanges content with [[PlanetMath]]; see [[WP:PMEX]]
*[http://mathworld.wolfram.com/ MathWorld] — See [[MathWorld]]

=== General reference ===
* [http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/User:Tim_Starling/ScanSet_TIFF_demo Encyclopaedia Brittanica 11/e] — This is full 1911 Encyclopedia Britanica. Its copyright has expired and its content is open to anyone.
* [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/ Perseus Digital Library] — This is an electronic library of source materials maintained by Tufts.
* [http://math.furman.edu/~mwoodard/mquot.html Mathematical Quotation Server] — This is a resource of Mathematics related quotations. It is maintained by Furman and is available for download.
* [http://www.ashep.com/archive/loQtus/homepage.html l o Q t u s] — This is a non-specific quotation database.
* [http://www.faqs.org faqs.org] —  A database of Internet related FAQs

=== General books online ===
* [http://digital.library.upenn.edu/books/ OnlineBooks] — a database of free books provided by U. Penn
* [http://www.archive.org/details/texts Internet Archive: Text Archive] —  An open access text archive licensed using Creative Commons licenses.

=== Historical mathematics ===
* [http://historical.library.cornell.edu/math/browse.html Cornell Historical Math] — A database of source materials. (Note: multiple entries will not be in English due to the nature of the sources.)
* [http://www.hti.umich.edu/u/umhistmath/ The University of Michigan Historical Mathematics Collection] — Similar to the Cornell database, provides texts from the 19th and 20th centuries and before.
* [http://dz-srv1.sub.uni-goettingen.de/cache/browse/AuthorMathematicaMonograph,WorkContainedA1.html GDZ - Göttingen digital collection] —  The majority of the works in this database are in German.
* [http://www.numdam.org/?lang=en NUMDAM - Numérisation de documents anciens mathématiques] — A collection of historical academic journals
* [http://perso.univ-rennes1.fr/antoine.chambert-loir/DJVU/ Antoine Chambert-Loir - Littérature mathématique en ligne] — small collection of source materials (site in French language)
* [http://www.math.dartmouth.edu/~euler/ The Euler Archive] — The collected works of Leonhard Euler.
* [http://dz-srv1.sub.uni-goettingen.de/cache/toc/D38910.html Gauss collected works] — This site and the works are in German
* [http://www.maths.tcd.ie/pub/HistMath/People/Hamilton/ Writings of Sir William Rowan Hamilton]
* [http://www.faculty.fairfield.edu/jmac/sjscient.htm Some Early Jesuit Scientists]
* [http://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp NASA Technical Reports Server] — searchable database of technical reports-requires javascript
* [http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/reprints/index.html Reprints in Theory and Applications of Categories] — a variety of papers involving category theory.
* [http://matwbn.icm.edu.pl ICM virtual library of science (Polish journals and monographs)] — Polish language site
*[http://www.dcs.warwick.ac.uk/bshm/gazetteer.html Mathematical Gazetteer of the British Isles] information about where mathematicians were born, lived, worked, died, or are buried or commemorated. Published by The British Society for the History of Mathematics.

=== Other mathematics ===
* [http://www.waukesha.uwc.edu/mat/kkromare/up.html Pronunciation Guide for Mathematics]
* [http://www.ams.org/mathweb/annser_f/ AMS Abbreviations of Names of Serials]
* [http://eom.springer.de/default.htm Encyclopædia of Mathematics]
* [http://eqworld.ipmnet.ru/ EqWorld] — for mathematical equations (mainly differential equations)
* [http://us2.metamath.org:8888/index.html Metamath Home Page] — illustrations of proofs
* [http://ocw.mit.edu/OcwWeb/Mathematics/index.htm MIT OpenCourseWare | Mathematics] — learning resource, essentially an E-classroom that allows you to attend selected courses at MIT
* [http://www.ams.org/online_bks/online-books-web.html AMS: Mathematics Books Online] — a small collection of online books
* [http://www.emis.de/monographs/links.html EMIS ELibM: Links to Mathematical Monographs and Lecture Notes] — links to other resources
* [http://www.geocities.com/alex_stef/mylist.html Alex Stefanov's list of textbooks, lecture notes and tutorials in mathematics] — a comprehensive list of free books of mathematics, organised by subject; includes the AMS books
* [http://www.math.gatech.edu/%7Ecain/textbooks/onlinebooks.html George Cain's list of online math texts] — diverse books of mathematics compiled by George Cain
* [http://www.jmilne.org/math/index.html Home Page J. S. Milne] - contains e-books and course notes
* [http://www.emis.de/projects/JFM/ The Jahrbuch Project: Electronic Research Archive for Mathematics] — extensive archive of 17,772 links to facsimiles of (mainly German) publications from 1868–1942.
* [http://mathdl.maa.org/mathDL/4/ MathDL: Journal of Online Mathematics and its Applications] — this is an MAA sub-journal.
* [http://journalseek.net/ JournalSeek - A Searchable Database of Online Scholarly Journals] — contains many hundreds of mathematics-related journals, organised by subject
* [http://www.intute.ac.uk/sciences/mathematics/ Intute: Science, Engineering and Technology - Mathematics] — a resource gateway, many of these resources require a subscription. If you are attached to a university you might have access to some of the resources listed
* [http://infomine.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/search?physci Physical Sciences, Engineering, Computing &amp; Math] — scholarly resource search-engine
* [http://torte.cs.berkeley.edu:8010/tilu TILU] — Table of Integrals Look Up
* [http://www.math.sfu.ca/~cbm/aands/ Abramowitz and Stegun: Handbook of Mathematical Functions] — available for download
* [http://web.comlab.ox.ac.uk/oucl/work/nick.trefethen/tools.html Numerical Software Tools] — list of databases, journals, tools, etc..
* [http://www-cgrl.cs.mcgill.ca/~godfried/teaching/cg-web.html Computational Geometry on the Web] — A variety of geometry related material.

==Online journals and preprints==
* [http://www.ams.org/global-preprints/ AMS Directory of Mathematics Preprint and e-Print Servers]
